            "description": "The projects urgency\n\nThe RITUS project starts with the wide-spread assumption that twenty-first century cities in the West witness a changing attitude towards the public significance of religion, grasped in the notion of \u2018the turn to the postsecular\u2019. This turn would delineate a turn away from secularism as ideology and practice, towards a non-secularist practice and stance towards religion in public policy and governance, in response to contemporary urban challenges to accommodate the rapidly diversifying religious landscape, to deal with the so-called return of religion in public life, to safeguard social cohesion and security, and to accommodate the so-called participation society, to which among others religious actors contribute.\n\nObjectives\n\nRITUS aims in the first place to describe and analyze the rapidly diversifying religious landscape in contemporary cities, with a particular focus on the migration of religion from conventional institutes to (1) art, (2) nature, (3) mediated networks, (4) religious innovative projects and (5) public space. In the second place, RITUS aims to analyze the challenges local governments are confronted with in this rapidly changing landscape, in particular with respect to religion in public life, and matters of social cohesion, security and quality of social life. Until recently, religious conversation partners were organized along traditional and institutional lines; the new religious landscape is far more diffuse, which makes it difficult for local governments to select representative conversational partners. In the third place, RITUS aims to contribute to theoretical debates on secularism and post-secularism as ideological guidelines for local governments.",
